===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|人|alt1=亻|山|ls=ic|ls2=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=person|t2=mountain}} — a person moving into a mountain to practise becoming immortal.

Originally {{zh-l|*僊}}. The current form is first attested in the clerical script of the Han dynasty.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=*僊,仚,屳,㒨-ancient,僲,𠑗-ancient,𠏡,𠇈}}
A relatively late word, perhaps {{der|zh|sit}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Compare {{cog|bo|གཤེན||shaman}}, as in {{cog|bo|གཤེན་རབ||Shenrab}}, the founder of the Tibetan religion {{w|Bon}}, although this might be a loan from Chinese ([[ibid]].).

{{zh-ref|Starostin}} sets up {{inh|zh|sit-pro||*s[ă]n|a kind of demon}}, comparing it to {{cog|bo|བསེན་མོ||female devil}} and {{cog|kac|sawn||malignant female [[nat]]}}. Note also, along similar lines, {{ncog|my|စုန်း|t=witch}}.

